  <bioghist id="afd27f486c2b06d29992d8b031b205a9">
    <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
<p>Ozzie Simmons (1919-1988) was a sociologist and anthropologist who worked for more than ten years at the Ford Foundation. Simmons started at the Foundation as a Program Advisor in the Latin America and the Caribbean, Chile Program. He then moved to the Population Program as a Program Officer. After that assignment, he worked for several years in the Asia and the Pacific, Southeast Asia Program where he was a Program Officer and then an Associate Representative/Program Officer. Simmons returned to the Population Program for a few years before he left the Foundation.</p><p>Prior to joining the Ford Foundation, Simmons worked as a lecturer and researcher at several institutions including the Smithsonian Institution, Harvard University, the University of Colorado, and Brandeis University. The American Psychiatric Association awarded him the Hofheimer Prize in 1962.</p><p>Simmons completed his undergraduate education at Northwestern University and earned master's and doctoral degrees from Harvard University. After he left the Ford Foundation, he joined the Fordham University Hispanic Research Center. Simmons died in 1988.</p>  </bioghist>
